Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt: 10:32 AM Defendant Tyler James Winter in court.  Attorney Jeffrey A Jaeger appeared by phone for Tyler James Winter.  Prosecuting attorney Joel N Urmanski in court for the State of Wisconsin. Defense filed bond motion, Deft would still like to address another issue. Deft requesting GPS to be removed. Atty Jaeger would like his Client to notify him if he's requesting anything to be modified, Atty Jaeger , victim no longer resides at address on bond, Deft is requesting no violent of abusive contact with victim as well. Deft makes statement as to where he is staying and did state he has had contact with victim. Court let Deft know he is already violating his bond. State has many concerns in this case, victim hasn't completed ERD program, and feels Deft is being untruthful, objects to modifying bond- would like the no contact to remain in place. Atty Jaeger reminds his Client he needs to remain in communication with him, Deft updated his phone number with the Court. Court does not modify bond at this time, no contact with victim or residence remains.
